Christine McVie, legendary singer-songwriter for the band Fleetwood Mac, passed away Wednesday after a brief illness.

'There are no words to describe our sadness at the passing of Christine McVie,' the band wrote on its official Twitter account. 'She was truly one-of-a-kind, special and talented beyond measure ... She will be so very missed.'

In two stints with Fleetwood Mac, from 1970 to 1998 and again from 2014 until her death, McVie penned some of the band's most recognizable tracks, from 'Everywhere,' to 'Don't Stop,' to 'You Make Loving Fun.' She was 79.

Megan Thee Stallion just made history by becoming the first Black woman on the cover of Forbes’ ’30 under 30’ issue. 

‘It’s really hard to be the first something in 2022, so ah!’ Megan told Forbes. 

In addition to being one of the biggest stars in the music industry and having lucrative deals with companies such as Netflix, Nike, and Popeyes, the Grammy-winning hip-hop artist also made headlines this year as an advocate for mental health. In her newest album, ‘Traumatize,’ Megan opens up about her experiences with topics such as mental illness and grief. 

When discussing the album, Megan told Forbes, ‘It made me feel happy that the time I did decide to be vulnerable and talk about something I was going through, it was one of the favorites from all of my fans... like it’s ok to not be ok and it’s ok to tell y’all I’m not ok.’

In September, Megan launched a website called ‘Bad Bitches Have Bad Days Too,’ which helps connect people with mental health resources, such as therapy and hotlines for drug abuse, suicide, and LGBTQ+ support. 

‘I want to be bigger than just my music,’ Megan added. ‘I’m trying to really build something.’

History will be made today at the World Cup in Qatar, but not by the players. For the first time in the tournament’s history, an all-women refereeing trio will take charge. Stéphanie Frappart, of France, Neuza Back, of Brazil, and Karen Diaz, of Mexico, will be refereeing the match between Costa Rica and Germany.

While Frappart will be the first woman lead referee during a men’s match at the World Cup, she isn’t new to making history. Previously, she was the first woman to be the lead referee for a men’s World Cup qualifying match, a men’s Champions League match, and the final match at the French Cup. She also served as the lead referee for the women’s World Cup in 2019.

‘They were not selected because they are women, but as FIFA referees,’ said Pierluigi Collina, chairman of the FIFA Referees Committee. ‘They could officiate any game.’

Emma Corrin, a British actor who previously won a Golden Globe for their portrayal of Princess Diana on ‘The Crown,’ is calling for an end to gendered acting awards. ‘When it comes to categories, do we need to make it specific as to whether you’re being nominated for a female role or a male role?’ they recently said in an interview with the BBC.

When they received the Golden Globe Award, Corrin was using she/her pronouns but has since come out as nonbinary and began publicly using they/them pronouns. They are starring in 2 high-profile films this year: ‘My Policeman’ and ‘Lady Chatterley’s Lover.’

‘It’s difficult for me at the moment trying to justify in my head being nonbinary and being nominated in female categories,’ they said.

But for Corrin, the roles being written also need to be expanded. ‘The conversation needs to be about having more representation in the material itself, in the content that we are seeing for nonbinary people, for queer people, for trans people, because then I think that will change a lot.’

In recent years, there have been rumors that the Oscars, Golden Globes, and Emmys have been having discussions on gender-neutral acting categories, but no changes have been announced. However, the Grammys, in 2012; the MTV Movie & TV Awards, in 2017; and the Independent Spirit Awards, in 2022, all eliminated gender-specific categories at their own ceremonies.

Kirstie Alley, best known for her role as Rebecca Howe on the beloved TV sitcom ‘Cheers,’ has passed away at the age 71. The actor had recently been diagnosed with cancer, according to a post uploaded to her official social media accounts Monday by her children, True and Lillie Parker.

‘We are sad to inform you that our incredible, fierce and loving mother has passed away after a battle with cancer, only recently discovered,’ they wrote.

‘She was surrounded by her closest family and fought with great strength, leaving us with a certainty of her never-ending joy of living and whatever adventures lie ahead,’ they added. ‘As iconic as she was on screen, she was an even more amazing mother and grandmother.’

Alley’s character Rebecca Howe first appeared in ‘Cheers’ in 1987, but it was 1991 that was her defining year on the show. That year, Alley took home both the Golden Globe and Primetime Emmy awards for lead actress in a comedy series for her performance on the show.

Tributes to Alley have begun pouring in from many Hollywood actors, including her friend and ‘Look Who's Talking’ co-star John Travolta. ‘Kirstie was one of the most special relationships I've ever had. I love you Kirstie,’ he wrote on Instagram.

Brittney Griner is officially out of Russian custody after being detained at a Moscow-area airport in February and receiving a 9-year sentence on drug-related charges.

Russia released the WNBA star in exchange for Russian arms dealer Viktor Bout, nicknamed the ‘Merchant of Death.’ He had served 11 years of a 25-year sentence in U.S. prison on charges including conspiring to kill American citizens.

President Joe Biden spoke Thursday morning to confirm the prisoner swap and told reporters that Griner will be in the U.S. 'within 24 hours.' Griner’s wife, Cherelle Griner, also spoke and said she is ‘overwhelmed with emotions’ following the athlete’s release.

‘She’s safe. She’s on a plane. She’s on her way home,’ Biden said at a press conference. ‘After months of being unjustly detained in Russia, held under intolerable circumstances, Brittney will soon be back in the arms of her loved ones, and, and she should have been there all along.’

Notably, the prisoner swap did not include former U.S. Marine Paul Whelan, who has been in Russian custody for almost 4 years. Biden told reporters Thursday his administration has not ‘forgotten’ Whelan or given up on his release.

Harvard University has tapped Claudine Gay to serve as the Ivy League institution’s next president, making her the first Black person and the second woman to hold the position. Her tenure is set to begin in July 2023.

Gay, who was born to Haitian immigrants, was herself a Harvard student and earned her PhD in government in 1998. She began teaching at Harvard in 2006 as a professor of government, also becoming a professor of African and African American studies in 2007.

She will succeed Lawrence S. Bacow, who will retire in June 2023 after 5 years of serving as Harvard’s president. He called Gay a ‘person of bedrock integrity’ and said he has faith that ‘she will provide Harvard with the strong moral compass necessary to lead this great university.’

Gay thanked the current president for guiding her throughout her time at Harvard and said it ‘has been a privilege to work with’ him. ‘He has shown me that leadership isn’t about one person. It’s about all of us, moving forward together. And that’s a lesson I take with me into this next journey,’ Gay said.

A plaza in Roanoke, VA, that once held a monument to Confederate General Robert E. Lee will now display a bronze statue of Henrietta Lacks instead.

Plans for the statue were announced at a local press conference on December 19. According to the NYT, nonprofit org Roanoke Hidden Histories raised more than $183,000 for the project, which will feature the work of sculptor Larry Bechtel and local artist Bryce Cobbs. The statue is expected to be ready by late 2023.

Henrietta Lacks was a Black woman born in Roanoke in 1920. As a young adult, Lacks contracted cervical cancer and ultimately died of the disease in 1951 at the age of 31. Before Lacks’ death, cells were taken from a biopsy of her tumor and sent to researchers at Johns Hopkins University.

Those cells were later cultured under the cell line HeLa, which in the years since, ‘has played a vital role in developing treatments for influenza, leukemia and Parkinson’s disease, as well as advancing chemotherapy, gene mapping, in vitro fertilization and more,’ per the NYT.

However, Lacks’ cells were originally taken without her consent, and for decades, her family didn’t know of her unwitting contributions to medical research, nor were they compensated for it. Lacks’ story gained greater prominence when science author Rebecca Skloot published the nonfiction book ‘The Immortal Life of Henrietta Lacks’ in 2010. It was subsequently adapted into a 2017 HBO film starring Oprah Winfrey.

A Texas couple who gave birth to twin daughters will have to celebrate the children’s birthdays on 2 separate days — and 2 separate years. That’s because first-time mommy Kali Jo Scott gave birth to her first baby girl, Annie Jo, at 11:55 pm local time on New Year’s Eve, then she gave birth to her second daughter, Effie Rose, just after midnight on New Year’s Day.

The fraternal twins were expected to arrive on January 11 via C-section, but Scott checked into the hospital weeks before her due date to allow doctors to monitor her blood pressure. The medical staff at the Texas hospital made the decision late in the night on December 31 to go forward with the C-section early.

Scott’s twin daughters both weighed around 5 pounds and 5 ounces. They are recovering and in healthy condition.

Looking ahead to how the twins might process their different birthdays moving forward, Scott says the uniqueness of the situation can play to both’s advantage in terms of feeling special on their own days.

'You always still want to make sure they have their own individual personality and know that they are special and unique. So this gets to add to that special and uniqueness that some twins don't maybe get,' she told local affiliate KDFW. 'One will always get the glitter and confetti of New Year's Eve and one gets to kick it off with a brand-new year on New Year's Day.'

Even though the odds of such an incident happening are staggeringly slim—about 1 in 2 million!—believe it or not, a twin birth of the very same kind occurred one year ago in Salinas, California. Fatima Madrigal gave birth to a baby boy, Alfredo, and his twin sister, Aylin, 15 minutes apart, placing them squarely in December 31, 2021, and January 1, 2022, respectively. We’ll have to wait another 12 months to see if anyone can make it a threepeat next December.

The U.S. Postal Service is honoring the late American novelist Toni Morrison with her own Forever stamp. It will feature a photo of her that was taken in 2000 and will be available for purchase beginning March 7.

In 1970, Morrison published her first book ‘The Bluest Eye,’ which was set in the 1940s and explored issues like racism and sexual abuse. Several U.S. school districts banned the book due to its subject matter. The American Library Association stated that it was banned and challenged ‘because it depicts child sexual abuse and was considered sexually explicit.’ Several of Morrison’s subsequent novels, like ‘Song of Solomon’ and ‘Beloved,’ have similarly been banned in certain school districts.

Despite attempts by some conservatives to limit the reach of Morrison’s work, her impact on 20th century American literature is undeniable. ‘Beloved’ in particular is seen as one of the greatest books of all time. It won the 1988 Pulitzer Prize for Fiction and is included on the BBC’s 2019 list of the 100 most influential novels of all time.

In 1993, Morrison became the first African American woman to win a Nobel Prize in Literature. She passed away on August 5, 2019, at the age of 88 due to pneumonia complications.

Other figures that will be honored with USPS Forever stamps this year include the late Supreme Court Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg, Ponca chief and Indigenous rights activist Standing Bear, and artist Roy Lichtenstein.

Ashley Manning began her flower business in 2020 and, like many florists, knew Valentine’s Day was a big day for her budding business. But Manning wanted to ensure nobody was left out of the holiday.

‘We’re kind of flipping the switch on love being celebrated by people with partners that day and we’re giving love to the people that actually need the love,’ Manning told Charlotte’s WCNC.

The initiative has grown each year. During the first program in 2021, Manning received hundreds of dollars in donations and was able to fulfill more than 100 surprise floral arrangements. In 2022, volunteers were able to surprise 400 widows with arrangements.

Even before the law initially passed in 2021, reproductive rights activists warned that Texas’ S.B. 8 (a.k.a. the Texas Heartbeat Act) could effectively turn state residents into ‘vigilantes’ and ‘bounty hunters’ against medical personnel and private citizens who were perceived as aiding pregnant people in seeking abortions. 

Marcus Silva filed the lawsuit on March 9 in Galveston County, reportedly seeking more than $1 million in damages from the women. Silva’s ex-wife was not named in the case, as she is exempt from liability under Texas law as the one who had the abortion.

Silva claims that two defendants shared information via text about how to end a pregnancy after his ex-wife discovered she was pregnant in July. It alleged the third defendant arranged for the delivery of the abortion medication. The women also allegedly discussed deleting their text messages about the abortion. Silva’s lawsuit is largely based on screenshots of text messages between the four women. 

His ex-wife filed for divorce in May, the Texas Tribune reports, citing court filings. The divorce was finalized last month, according to the lawsuit. 

Silva is being represented by Republican state Rep. Briscoe Cain, as well as Jonathan Mitchell, a former solicitor general who helped draft the Texas Heartbeat Act. 

‘This is an outrageous attempt to scare people from getting abortion care and intimidate those who support their friends, family, and community in their time of need,’ Autumn Katz, a Center for Reproductive Rights lawyer, said in a statement. ‘The extremists behind this lawsuit are twisting the law and judicial system to threaten and harass people seeking essential care and those who help them.’

Last year, Wong was honored with her own quarter by the U.S. Mint, alongside 4 other women: Dr. Maya Angelou, Dr. Sally Ride, Wilma Mankiller, and Nina Otero-Warren. That honor made her the first Asian American to grace U.S. currency.

A major U.S. health panel just issued a new recommendation for women to start seeking mammograms 10 years earlier, at 40 instead of 50. The task force also notes that ​​Black women ‘often get deadly cancers at younger ages,’ and issued a call ‘for more research to understand the underlying causes and what can be done to eliminate this health disparity.’

‘Ensuring Black women start screening at age 40 is an important first step, yet it is not enough to improve the health inequities we face related to breast cancer,’ said task force vice chair Wanda Nicholson.

The draft recommendation still needs to be reviewed and finalized. It is open for public comment through June 5, at which point the panel will revisit the proposal.

The family of Henrietta Lacks has reached a settlement with a biotechnology company that continually used her cells, according to the family's lawyer Ben Crump.

Known as HeLa cells, they were the first human cells to be successfully cloned. Since then, HeLa cells have played a pivotal role in modern medicine, enabling numerous scientific breakthroughs, including the development of genetic mapping and the polio and COVID-19 vaccines.

However, the Lacks family never received any compensation as a result of the cells' use. The family's lawyers argued that Thermo Fisher Scientific Inc., a Massachusetts-based biotech firm, ‘continued to commercialize the results well after the origins of the HeLa cell line became well known,’ according to the Associated Press.

‘It is outrageous that this company would think that they have intellectual rights property to their grandmother’s cells. Why is it they have intellectual rights to her cells and can benefit billions of dollars when her family, her flesh and blood, her Black children, get nothing?’ Crump said in October 2021.

The terms of the agreement are confidential, according to both Crump and representatives for Thermo Fisher. The settlement was announced on August 1, on what would have been Lacks’ 103rd birthday. 

‘There couldn’t have been a more fitting day for her to have justice, for her family to have relief,’ said Lacks' grandson Alfred Lacks Carter Jr., via the AP.

The first pill to treat postpartum depression was greenlit by the FDA on August 4. Zuranolone, sold under the brand name zurzuvae, is administered as a once-daily pill taken over the course of 14 days.

Farchione, director of the Division of Psychiatry at the FDA's Center for Drug Evaluation and Research, wrote in a statement. 'Having access to an oral medication will be a beneficial option for many of these women coping with extreme, and sometimes life-threatening, feelings.'

Clinical trials have shown that zuranolone works rapidly, with its effects beginning in as little as 3 days. That's significantly faster than traditional antidepressants, which may take several weeks to take effect. Zuranolone is expected to be available after a 90-day review by the Drug Enforcement Administration, which is a required step for drugs affecting the central nervous system.

According to nonprofit group Period, which was co-founded by Okamoto, 23% of U.S. teens have struggled to buy period products in 2023, with lower-income students and students of color—especially Latine students—disproportionately impacted by the lack of access.

'Really what we are trying to say is that [period products] should fall into the category of medical necessities,' said Okamoto. The 'Black Panther' and 'What's Love Got to Do with It' actor received an honorary Academy Award on January 9.

'I proudly share this honor with women who stand up when they are told to stand back, who speak up when they are silenced, who remain determined when they are told they are defeated,' Bassett said in her acceptance speech.

'When I wake up in my own pink world!' 🥹💞 

Christina, mom to 3-year-old Riley, shared this video of her daughter watching a version of ‘Barbie’ that had an ASL interpreter on screen.

The movie is interpreted by Leila Hanaumi, who’s on screen during its duration.

Christina said her daughter, whose first language is ASL, was engaged in the movie but also learned new signs while watching the interpreter.

‘It has been incredible to watch my daughter Riley, who is deaf, watch this movie,' Christina said on Instagram. 'If you have HBO, please give this a watch—one because it’s awesome and you’ll love it, but also because, I have to imagine, if the version with ASL gets a lot of views, HBO and others will continue to feature ASL interpreters on screen for future movies and shows.’

What’s that? A crazy, funky, junky reboot?

Disney is set to revive our favorite childhood sitcom ‘Wizards of Waverly Place,’ with a pilot episode already in the works. @selenagomez and @davidhenrie, who played two of the Russo siblings, are executive producing the project alongside Jed Elinoff and Scott Thomas, who helped create the ‘Raven’s Home’ reboot.

Gomez will be making a guest appearance in the pilot, reprising her role as Alex. Henrie will reprise his role as Justin, who is now a father who chooses to forgo his wizarding powers for a normal life with his wife and two sons, according to Deadline.

New cast members include Alkaio Thiele, Mimi Gianopulos, and Janice LeAnn Brown.
